Back in Ye Olde Days of Ye Dial-Uppe, non-animated static .gif was a pretty common format for images, especially if they were scanned from printed material. .jpeg didn't become commonplace until Compuserve decided that they owned the .gif format and decided everyone everywhere on the Internet owed them royalties. It didn't end well for them, and .jpeg, with lossy compression that was still good enough for people using Windows 3.1 and glass tube monitors at 640x480, gave smaller file sizes anyway--critical when you were connected at 14.4k on a phone line. I will guess that someone changed the format of that image some time in the past twenty-five or thirty years.
